    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, you are absolutely correct that it is the interaction between amino acids (proteins) and reducing sugars, but the reaction is heavily influenced by pH levels, moisture content, and temperature. Lower pH levels (more acidic environments) actually accelerate the Maillard reaction, while high moisture inside the oven can slow it down since water vapor absorbs heat and inhibits the necessary surface dehydration. Your instructor is right about the environment because steam from the dough initially prevents browning, so you must wait until the crust dries out enough before the browning process can truly intensify. Think of it as a delicate balance where too much moisture or the wrong pH will keep your bread pale, while the right conditions create that perfect golden crust.",
